Fundamentals of Data Visualization Final Project

  1. Dataset Overview and Source

For my project, I have chosen the Superstore dataset, which is widely used in data analytics demonstrations. It simulates sales data for a retail store covering multiple product categories, regions, and time periods. You can find various versions of this dataset on sites like Tableau.

Most versions of this dataset span multiple years (2014–2017) and include around 10,000 rows. This makes it a moderately sized, tabular dataset—complex enough to yield interesting insights. Due to Altairs row limitations most of my exploration will be done with aggegrate data.

  1. Goals and Key Questions

Overall Goal:

My primary goal is to understand sales performance and profitability across different product categories, sub-categoires and states.

Specific Questions:

  • What correlations exist within our data that are strongly linked to sales and profit?
    • Answer analysis and code to support assertion found below: Based on the creation of correlation matrix's and heatmaps, this data does not have any "Strong Correlation" the strongest correlation we have is between sales and profit (.48 correlation) which would be considered a moderate correlation.
  • Which product categories and sub-categories yield the highest sales and profit?
    • Answer analysis and code to support assertion found below: The category with the highest profit is "Technology" and the highest profitable sub-category is "Copiers".
  • What states account for the most sales and profit?
    • Answer analysis and code to support assertion found below: Based on the analysis below the top 3 most profitable states are: California, New York and Washington.
  1. Key Elements of Design

All of my visualizations had to do with 'profit' as such I chose to focus on a simple and intutive color scheme. If a category, subcategory or state was profitable it green and if it was not profitable it is red. For more consumers this is inline with what they would assume and allows for easier digestion of the visualizations.

  1. Evaluation of Approach

I evaluated my deisgn choice with several non-technical family members to see if my approach was simple and approachable. Based on my straigh forward design choices they were all able to accurately and quickly understand the data presented.

  1. Synthesis of Findings

Overall, my approach was effective—I efficiently completed my core objective. However, I recognize that this dataset offers virtually limitless insights. In the future, I plan to conduct a more comprehensive analysis to uncover additional trends and conclusions. For now, I focused on a targeted analysis due to time constraints.

Question 1: What correlations exist within our data that are strongly linked to sales and profit?

In [5]:
#Creating a heatmap to identify correlations between numeric variables
numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include='number').drop(columns=['Row ID'])
corr_matrix = numeric_df.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
heatmap = sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f')
plt.show()
In [6]:
# Encoding categorical data to view correlations
df_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df[['Order Date', 'Ship Mode', 'Segment', 'Region', 'Category']], drop_first=True)

numeric_df = df.select_dtypes(include='number').drop(columns=['Row ID', 'Postal Code'])
combined_df = pd.concat([numeric_df, df_dummies], axis=1)
corr_matrix = combined_df.corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
heatmap = sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f')
plt.show()
In [7]:
#Since Altair has a 5000 row limit ill have to take a sample of my data
sample = df.sample(n=3000, random_state=42)

selector = alt.selection_point(fields=['Profit'], on='mouseover', nearest=True, bind='legend')

chart = alt.Chart(sample).mark_point().encode(
    x='Profit',
    y='Sales',
    tooltip=['Sales', 'Profit'],
    color=alt.condition('datum.Profit < 0', alt.value('red'), alt.value('green')),
    opacity=alt.condition(selector, alt.value(1), alt.value(0.3)),
    size=alt.Size('Profit').scale(range=[10, 150])
).add_params(
    selector
).properties(
    height=300,
    width=600,
    title=alt.TitleParams(
        text='Correlation between sales and profit',
        subtitle='Red indicates negative profit while green indicates positive profit',
        fontSize=20, 
        subtitleFontSize=14
            )
).interactive()

Question 2: Which product categories and sub-categories yield the highest sales and profit?

In [8]:
#Determining categories with highest sales and profit
category_query = (
    df.groupby('Category', as_index=False)
    .agg({'Profit': 'sum', 'Sales': 'sum'})
    .sort_values('Profit', ascending= False))

category_query = category_query.reset_index(drop=True)  
category_query.index = category_query.index + 1        
category_query.index.name = 'Rank'  

category_query['Profit Margin'] = ((category_query['Profit'] / category_query['Sales']) *100)

for col in ['Profit', 'Sales']:
    category_query[col] = category_query[col].apply(lambda x: f"${x:.2f}")

category_query['Profit Margin'] = category_query['Profit Margin'].apply(lambda x: f"{x:.2f}%")

title = "Profit, Sales & Profit Margin by Category"
centered_title = title.center(55)  
bold_centered_title = f"\033[1m{centered_title}\033[0m"
print(bold_centered_title)

category_query.style

#Creating interactive chart for highest profit categories 
# Creating interactive chart for highest profit categories 
import ipywidgets as widgets
from ipywidgets import interact
import plotly.express as px  # assuming this is already installed

cat_data = (
    df.groupby('Category', as_index=False)
      .agg({'Sales': 'sum', 'Profit': 'sum'})
      .sort_values('Profit', ascending=False)
)

custom_scale = [(0.0, 'red'), (0.5, 'white'), (1.0, 'green')]

widget = interact(
    lambda Top: (
        px.bar(
            cat_data[:Top],
            x='Category',
            y='Profit',
            color='Profit',
            labels={'Category': "Product Category", 'Profit': 'Total Profit'},
            template='plotly_dark',
            text='Profit',
            color_continuous_scale=custom_scale,
            color_continuous_midpoint=0
        )
        .update_layout(
            xaxis_tickangle=-45,
            yaxis={'visible': True, 'showticklabels': True, 'showgrid': False},
            font=dict(size=12)
        )
        .update_traces(
            showlegend=False,
            texttemplate='$%{y:.2f}',
            textposition='auto'
        )
    ),
    Top=widgets.IntSlider(min=1, max=len(cat_data), step=1, value=3)
)

interactive(children=(IntSlider(value=3, description='Top', max=3, min=1), Output()), _dom_classes=('widget-in…

state = (df.groupby('State', as_index= False)
         .agg({'Profit':'sum', 'Sales':'sum'})
         .sort_values('Profit', ascending= False)).head()

state = state.reset_index(drop= True)
state.index += 1
state.index.name = 'Rank'

state['Profit Margin'] = ((state['Profit'] / state['Sales']) * 100).apply(lambda x: f"{x:.2f}%")

for col in ['Profit', 'Sales']:
    state[col] = state[col].apply(lambda x: f"${x:.2f}")

title = 'Sales, Profit and Profit Margin by State'
centered_title = title.center(55)

print(bold_centered_title)

import requests

state_data = df.groupby('State', as_index=False).agg({
    'Sales': 'sum',
    'Profit': 'sum'
})

url = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/PublicaMundi/MappingAPI/master/data/geojson/us-states.json"
states_geojson = requests.get(url).json()

fig = px.choropleth_map(
    state_data,
    geojson=states_geojson,
    locations='State',             
    featureidkey="properties.name", 
    color='Profit',                
    color_continuous_scale=[(0.0, 'red'), (0.5, 'white'), (1.0, 'green')],
    color_continuous_midpoint=0,    
    map_style="carto-darkmatter",
    zoom=3,
    center={"lat": 37.0902, "lon": -95.7129},
    opacity=0.7,
    height=600,
    template='plotly_dark'
)

fig.update_layout(margin={"r":0,"t":0,"l":0,"b":0})
fig.show()

Based on the analysis above the top 3 most profitable states are: California, New York and Washington
